I just found how to trigger it much easier, not having to use the internals:
```
#include <curl/curl.h>
extern "C" int
LLVMFuzzerTestOneInput(const uint8_t* rawdata, size_t rawsize)
{
  std::istringstream iss(std::string((const char*)rawdata,rawsize+(const char*)rawdata));
  CURL* handle =  curl_easy_init();
  std::string line;
  while (std::getline(iss, line)) {
          curl_easy_setopt(handle, CURLOPT_COOKIELIST,line.c_str());
      }
  curl_easy_setopt(handle, CURLOPT_COOKIEJAR, "/dev/null");
  curl_easy_perform(handle);
  curl_easy_cleanup(handle);
  return 0;
}
```

Ok, I can now reproduce it with a vanilla setup. First I compile curl from master, using the following steps
```
# in curl
./buildconf
./configure --prefix /tmp/slafs
make
make install
```
and then the following program
```
#include <vector>
#include <fstream>
#include <curl/curl.h>

int main(int argc, char* argv[]) {
    for(int i=1; i<argc; ++i) {
        std::ifstream iss(argv[i]);
        if(!iss) {continue;}

        CURL* handle =  curl_easy_init();

        std::string line;
        while (std::getline(iss, line)) {
                curl_easy_setopt(handle, CURLOPT_COOKIELIST,line.c_str());
            }

        curl_easy_setopt(handle, CURLOPT_COOKIEJAR, "/dev/null");
        curl_easy_perform(handle);

        curl_easy_cleanup(handle);
    }
}
```
compiled with (the optimization level is not important, and neither is the compiler, works with clang as well)
```
g++ easy.cc -O3 -I /tmp/slafs/include/ -L /tmp/slafs/lib/ -lcurl
```
and then invoked with
```
export LD_LIBRARY_PATH=/tmp/slafs/lib
 ./a.out 323361f03b8d0424ba2e32729828596a16837f8c
```
which gives a segfault. running it through valgrind also gives errors.

Stripping out the C++ from the example, isn't this doing the same thing? I'm not sure what the loop around getline() accomplishes?
~~~c
#include <curl/curl.h>

int main(int argc, char* argv[])
{
  for(int i=1; i<argc; ++i) {
    CURL *handle =  curl_easy_init();
    curl_easy_setopt(handle, CURLOPT_COOKIELIST, argv[i]);
    curl_easy_setopt(handle, CURLOPT_COOKIEJAR, "/dev/null");
    curl_easy_perform(handle);
    curl_easy_cleanup(handle);
  }
}

# what happens

1. `c->numcookies` is the total number of cookies kept in the jar.
2. When saving the cookies, the code iterates over them to build an array so that it can sort them with `qsort()`
3. in that [loop](https://github.com/curl/curl/blob/2a2404153bb427a8c4b046a96389fc9862944aa3/lib/cookie.c#L1542-L1548) it *excludes* cookies that don't have a 'domain'  property and uses `j` to count.the valid ones
4. when later [invoking qsort](https://github.com/curl/curl/blob/2a2404153bb427a8c4b046a96389fc9862944aa3/lib/cookie.c#L1550) it uses `c->numcookies` instead of the correct counter `j` as they may now differ (if there are cookies in memory without domain)!

# impact

`qsort()` gets invoked and will read uninitialized pointers from the malloc()ed array.

# security flaw?

Can this be triggered by "someone" and what can said "someone" do with it?

To get a cookie set without a domain it needs to be read from a file or set with the API, as when receiving cookies over the wire with HTTP there's always a default domain. I don't think a malicious site can trigger this.

An application that allows the user to pass in a cookie file or cookie values at startup can be made to trigger this. But can that be considered a security problem? I don't think so. Or maybe my imagination is just too weak?

# fix

I'd like to fix it in two ways.

1. Use `j` in the qsort() line
2. Filter out cookies without domain already when set

